   787	
   788	## Review gate
   789	
   790	Before handing to `/codex-review`:
   791	
   792	- The plan answers, for each of the five design decisions, what the
   793	  chosen option is and why the alternatives were rejected:
   794	  - **Quiescence by iteration counter vs by event subscription.**
   795	    Counter chosen because (a) it matches how `run_experiment`
   796	    already detects quiescence and (b) doesn't require the worker
   797	    hosts to distinguish "I'm idle" from "I exited" on the
   798	    subscriber end.
   799	  - **Workers poll tasks vs subscribe to events.** Polling chosen
   800	    for 8b because teardown (kill at any moment) is trivial and
   801	    because the poll interval is a single tunable. Event-subscribe
   802	    remains a future optimization.
   803	  - **Shared-token in normative vocabulary vs reference-only
   804	    namespace.** Reference-only chosen because the spec chapter
   805	    07 explicitly defers auth to Milestone 3 and committing to a
   806	    shape now would force rework then.
   807	  - **Common scaffolding extracted vs inlined per service.**
   808	    Extracted because three divergent CLIs are the predictable
   809	    failure mode and because the extraction is small (< 200 LOC).
   810	  - **Service directories — reuse stubs vs new names.** Reuse the
   811	    four existing Phase 0 stubs (`planner/`, `implementer/`,
   812	    `evaluator/`, `orchestrator/`) — they are the roadmap's blessed
   813	    names and [`reference/README.md`](../../reference/README.md)
   814	    already documents them. Add one new directory
   815	    (`task-store-server/`) for the process that holds the store;
   816	    there is no stub because Phase 0 didn't anticipate splitting
   817	    the store off. The Phase 8a plan's tentative
   818	    `orchestrator-service/` name was a placeholder while the
   819	    directory didn't yet exist; now that it's being created for
   820	    real, the shorter stub name is the better pick.
   821	
   822	(The last decision is flagged for codex review to push back if the
   823	rename is the wrong tradeoff.)

 succeeded in 0ms:
   261	**Scripted logic across the subprocess boundary.** Today
   262	`ScriptedPlanner` / `ScriptedImplementer` / `ScriptedEvaluator` take
   263	user-supplied Python callables (`plan_fn`, `implement_fn`,
   264	`evaluate_fn`) at construction. That arrangement does not survive
   265	being put behind a CLI — Python callables don't cross a
   266	`python -m eden_planner_host …` boundary.
   267	
   268	8b resolves this by **baking one built-in profile into each worker
   269	host**. A new module `reference/services/_common/scripted.py` owns
   270	the canonical 8b profile: the same deterministic "3 trials, all
   271	succeed" shape the Phase 5 / 7b in-process tests use today, with a
   272	couple of knobs configurable via CLI rather than by injecting a
   273	function:
   274	
   275	- Planner host: fixed `plan_fn` that drafts `--proposals-per-plan`
   276	  proposals per task (default `1`) with deterministic slugs derived
   277	  from the plan task ID.
   278	- Implementer host: fixed `implement_fn` that writes a real git
   279	  commit to the shared bare repo (see "Implementer repo model"
   280	  below) and returns its SHA. `--fail-every N` (default: never
   281	  fail) flips occasional trials to `status=error` to exercise
   282	  rejection paths in tests.
   283	- Evaluator host: fixed `evaluate_fn` that returns scripted metrics
   284	  matching the experiment's `metrics_schema` (read from
   285	  `--experiment-config` so the evaluator knows what keys to emit).
   286	  `--fail-every N` flips occasional evaluations to
   287	  `status=error` / `status=eval_error` if a test wants them.
   288	
   289	The `ScriptedPlanner` / `ScriptedImplementer` / `ScriptedEvaluator`
   290	classes stay callable-injected for Phase 5 / 7b in-process tests —
   291	the worker hosts are the only callers that wrap them in the fixed
   292	profile. This way nothing about the in-process test surface changes.
   293	
   294	Selector: a `--profile NAME` CLI flag is **not** introduced in 8b —
   295	the fixed profile is the only option. When real LLM-backed workers
   296	land (Phase 10 LLM hosts), they ship as separate worker hosts
   297	(`eden_llm_planner_host`, etc.) rather than as a `--profile llm`
   298	switch on the scripted host. Keeping the split explicit at the
   299	binary level means the scripted and LLM hosts don't share
   300	configuration surfaces that each only half-understands.
   301	
   302	**Implementer repo model.** The `Integrator` requires that the
   303	`commit_sha` an implementer submits be a real, reachable commit on
   304	a branch it can read
   305	([integrator.py](../../reference/packages/eden-git/src/eden_git/integrator.py) §2
   306	preconditions). Today's Phase 7b E2E fixture satisfies this by
   307	prebuilding real `work/*` branches before running the experiment
   308	and returning those real SHAs from the scripted `implement_fn`.
   309	Phase 8b needs the equivalent inside a standalone process.
   310	
   311	Decision: the implementer host writes real commits directly, via a
   312	`GitRepo` opened against the **same bare repo** the orchestrator's
   313	`Integrator` reads from.
   314	
   315	- Implementer CLI gains `--repo-path PATH` — the bare repo it
   316	  writes to. Same path the orchestrator passes to `--repo-path`.
   317	- Implementer's scripted flow per task writes an **orphan commit**
   318	  (no parents) on a fresh `work/*` branch. This matches the
   319	  scripted planner's proposals, which emit empty
   320	  `parent_commits=()`, and keeps planner and implementer decoupled
   321	  from any shared base-ref convention:
   322	  1. Build a tree containing one deterministic blob (filename
   323	     derived from the proposal slug, content derived from the
   324	     trial ID) via `GitRepo.write_blob` + `write_tree_from_entries`.
   325	  2. `commit_tree` with that tree, **no parents**, fixed author /
   326	     committer identity, deterministic message derived from the
   327	     proposal slug + trial ID.
   328	  3. `create_ref refs/heads/work/<slug>-<trial_id>` → new SHA.
   329	  4. Submit the new SHA on the implement task.
   330	
   331	  Because proposals carry `parent_commits=()`, the Integrator's
   332	  §1.4 reachability check over `trial.parent_commits` iterates an
   333	  empty sequence and trivially passes; the §2 check that
   334	  `commit_sha` is reachable from `branch` is satisfied by the
   335	  branch ref the implementer just wrote pointing at that SHA.
   336	
   337	This keeps the implementer host's write path identical to how the
   338	Phase 7b test prebuilds branches, just inside the service loop
   339	rather than in a test fixture. Concurrency is fine: worker hosts
   340	only write `work/*` refs; the orchestrator's `Integrator` only
   341	writes `trial/*` refs and reads `work/*` refs. Git's packed-refs +
   342	loose-refs arrangement is safe under concurrent writers in
   343	distinct ref namespaces.
   344	
   345	**ID allocation across restarts.** Counter-based prefixes
   346	(`proposal-1`, `proposal-2`, …) collide on restart because a fresh
   347	worker has no knowledge of persisted state. Decision: worker-
   348	generated IDs (`proposal_id`, `trial_id`) are short UUIDv4 hex
   349	strings prefixed by a role tag — `proposal-<uuid>`, `trial-<uuid>`.
   350	The `--proposal-prefix` / `--trial-prefix` flags are dropped; the
   351	orchestrator-allocated task IDs keep `--implement-task-prefix` /
   352	`--evaluate-task-prefix` (because those are used for human-readable
   353	IDs in logs and E2E assertions), but the per-iteration uniqueness
   354	comes from appending a short UUID.
   355	
   356	The E2E test asserts on the *count* and *shape* of produced IDs,
   357	not specific values — so UUIDs are fine. Plan task IDs remain
   358	explicit (`--plan-tasks plan-1,plan-2,plan-3`) because the harness
   359	needs to reference them in assertions.
   360	
   361	### Shared-token auth scaffolding (reference-only)
   362	
   363	**Server-side extension** in `eden_wire.server`:
   364	
   365	```python
   366	def make_app(
   367	    store: Store,
   368	    *,
   369	    subscribe_timeout: float = 30.0,
   370	    subscribe_poll_interval: float = 0.1,
   371	    shared_token: str | None = None,
   372	) -> FastAPI:
   373	    ...
   374	    if shared_token is not None:
   375	        app.add_middleware(_SharedTokenMiddleware, token=shared_token)
   376	    ...
   377	```
   378	
   379	The middleware runs before endpoint dispatch. It:
   380	
   381	- Accepts any request whose `Authorization: Bearer <value>` matches
   382	  `shared_token` byte-for-byte (constant-time compare via
   383	  `hmac.compare_digest`).
   384	- Rejects any other request (missing header, wrong scheme, wrong
   385	  value) with a problem+json envelope:
   386	
   387	  ```json
   388	  {
   389	    "type": "eden://reference-error/unauthorized",
   390	    "title": "Unauthorized",
   391	    "status": 401,
   392	    "detail": "missing or invalid Authorization header",
   393	    "instance": "…request URL…"
   394	  }
   395	  ```
   396	
   397	Notes:
   398	
   399	- The `type` URI namespace `eden://reference-error/…` is **separate**
   400	  from the normative `eden://error/…` namespace in
   401	  [`spec/v0/07-wire-protocol.md`](../../spec/v0/07-wire-protocol.md)
   402	  §7. A conforming server that uses a different auth mechanism is
   403	  free to emit whatever type it likes (or no auth at all).
   404	- The middleware does not guard the `/docs` / `/openapi.json` routes
   405	  any differently; both require the token when auth is enabled.
   406	- When `shared_token is None`, no middleware is installed; the server
   407	  behaves exactly as today. Every existing `make_app(store)` call site
   408	  works unchanged.
   409	
   410	**Client-side extension** in `eden_wire.client`:
   411	
   412	```python
   413	class StoreClient:
   414	    def __init__(
   415	        self,
   416	        base_url: str,
   417	        experiment_id: str,
   418	        *,
   419	        token: str | None = None,
   420	        ...
   421	    ) -> None:
   422	        ...
   423	```
   424	
   425	When `token` is set, every request carries
   426	`Authorization: Bearer <token>`. The client also recognizes the
   427	reference-only error type and raises a new
   428	`eden_wire.errors.Unauthorized(ReferenceError)` subclass, so calling
   429	code can catch it explicitly. `Unauthorized` is not a `StorageError`
   430	subclass — authentication is transport-level, not store-level.
   431	
   432	**Spec addendum.** A new informative subsection §8 "Reference-only
   433	extensions" in `spec/v0/07-wire-protocol.md`, ~10 lines:
   434	
   435	> Authentication is outside the normative binding (§7 restates
   436	> this). The reference implementation in
   437	> [`reference/packages/eden-wire/`](../../reference/packages/eden-wire/)
   438	> ships an optional shared-token check: when configured, the server
   439	> requires `Authorization: Bearer <token>` on every request and
   440	> rejects others with a problem+json response whose `type` is
   441	> `eden://reference-error/unauthorized`. Conforming servers MAY
   442	> adopt this scheme, adopt a different scheme, or require no
   443	> authentication at all. The only constraint §7 imposes on any
   444	> auth scheme is that it MUST NOT emit error `type` values inside
   445	> the normative `eden://error/…` namespace — the v0 vocabulary
   446	> there is closed, and an auth-outcome type overloading one of
   447	> those values would force clients to disambiguate auth from
   448	> store-state errors on HTTP status alone.
   449	
   450	### `eden-dispatch` refactor
   451	
   452	Today `run_experiment(store, planner, implementer, evaluator, ...)`
   453	interleaves:
   454	
   455	1. `planner.run_pending(store)`
   456	2. `_finalize_submitted(store, kind="plan")`
   457	3. `_dispatch_implement_tasks(store, ...)`
   458	4. `implementer.run_pending(store)`
   459	5. `_finalize_submitted(store, kind="implement")`
   460	6. `_dispatch_evaluate_tasks(store, ...)`
   461	7. `evaluator.run_pending(store)`
   462	8. `_finalize_submitted(store, kind="evaluate")`
   463	9. `_promote_successful_trials(store, integrate_trial)` (optional)
   464	
   465	Steps 2, 3, 5, 6, 8, 9 are orchestrator-only; 1, 4, 7 are worker-only.
   466	Factor out `_run_orchestrator_iteration(store, *, integrate_trial,
   467	implement_task_factory, evaluate_task_factory)` that does steps
   468	2, 3, 5, 6, 8, 9 and returns `progress: bool`.
   469	
   470	`run_experiment` becomes:
   471	
   472	```python
   473	def run_experiment(store, planner, implementer, evaluator, *, ...):
   474	    for task_id in plan_task_ids:
   475	        store.create_plan_task(task_id)
   476	    while True:
   477	        progress = False
   478	        progress |= planner.run_pending(store) > 0
   479	        progress |= implementer.run_pending(store) > 0
   480	        progress |= evaluator.run_pending(store) > 0
   481	        progress |= _run_orchestrator_iteration(store, ...)
   482	        if not progress:
   483	            return
   484	```
   485	
   486	— identical behavior, but the orchestrator half is now importable
   487	from a single function that the new orchestrator can call.
   488	
   489	The worker-host processes consume `planner.run_pending(client)` etc.
   490	directly and don't touch `run_experiment`.
   491	
   492	### Tests
   493	
   494	New test files, in rough order of ambition:
   495	
   496	1. **Unit — auth middleware**
   497	   (`reference/packages/eden-wire/tests/test_auth.py`). Requests with
   498	   correct / missing / wrong-scheme / wrong-value headers hit a
   499	   `make_app(store, shared_token="T")` via `TestClient`; assert the
   500	   status + problem+json envelope shape. Also assert that
   501	   `make_app(store)` without `shared_token` admits anonymous
   502	   requests (regression guard on the default path).
   503	
   504	2. **Unit — StoreClient auth header**
   505	   (`reference/packages/eden-wire/tests/test_auth.py` same file). A
   506	   `StoreClient(token="T")` routed through `MockTransport` captures
   507	   the outgoing `Authorization` header; with no token, no
   508	   `Authorization` header is sent.
   509	
   510	3. **Unit — `run_orchestrator_iteration` against a seeded store**
   511	   (`reference/packages/eden-dispatch/tests/test_orchestrator_iteration.py`).
   512	   For each of the six transitions the function performs, pre-seed a
   513	   store so exactly one transition is applicable, call the function,
   514	   assert the expected state change plus `progress is True`. Then a
   515	   fully-quiesced store returns `progress is False`.
   516	
   517	4. **Unit — each worker host in isolation**
   518	   (`reference/services/<role>/tests/test_host.py`). Boot the
   519	   service's `host.run(...)` in a thread with a `StoreClient` backed
   520	   by an in-process `TestClient`, seed a pending task, wait for the
   521	   terminal state, assert outcome, `stopping.set()` to tear down.
   522	   Proves the host's poll loop honors SIGTERM semantics without
   523	   forking subprocesses.
   524	
   525	5. **Unit — task-store-server app construction**
   526	   (`reference/services/task-store-server/tests/test_app.py`). Loads
   527	   the fixture experiment config, calls
   528	   `app.build_app(args)`, asserts the returned FastAPI has the
   529	   middleware installed iff `--shared-token` was passed.
   530	
   531	6. **Integration — real-subprocess E2E**
   532	   (`reference/services/orchestrator/tests/test_e2e.py`).
   533	   Uses `subprocess.Popen` with `python -m eden_task_store_server`,
   534	   `python -m eden_planner_host`, etc. The harness:
   535	
   536	   - Creates a tempdir; `git init --bare` inside. The implementer
   537	     writes orphan commits on `work/*` branches, so no seed commit
   538	     is required.
   539	   - Creates a tempdir for the sqlite DB (`--db-path` pointing at a
   540	     file, not `:memory:` — this exercises the SQLite path end-to-end).
   541	   - Boots task-store-server on `--port 0`, reads
   542	     `EDEN_TASK_STORE_LISTENING` from stdout to learn the port, then
   543	     boots 3 workers + orchestrator against
   544	     `http://127.0.0.1:<port>`. The implementer and orchestrator
   545	     both point `--repo-path` at the bare repo; the planner and
   546	     evaluator don't touch it. All 5 subprocesses share
   547	     `--shared-token test-token` to exercise auth.
   548	   - Waits up to 60 seconds for the orchestrator to exit 0.
   549	   - On timeout or non-zero exit, dumps every subprocess's stderr
   550	     into the pytest failure output (this is non-negotiable — the
   551	     one thing that makes subprocess tests diagnosable is capturing
   552	     every process's stderr on failure).
   553	   - SIGTERMs the workers and task-store-server; awaits each for up
   554	     to 10 seconds, then SIGKILLs.
   555	   - Opens the DB with a fresh `SqliteStore`, asserts:
   556	     - 3 accepted plan tasks, 3 accepted implement tasks, 3 accepted
   557	       evaluate tasks.
   558	     - 3 trials with `status="success"` and `trial_commit_sha` set.
   559	     - Each `trial_commit_sha` is a valid git commit in the bare repo.
   560	   - Tears down tempdirs.

